references: In this section, we investigate the potential for combining TextSimu with traditional injection poisoning attacks to enhance the overall effectiveness of such attacks. We specifically employ Random-Attacks (RA) and Bandwagon-Attacks (BA) as instances to test the integration with TextSimu. The data results presented in Table 3 demonstrate that TextSimu can indeed be enhanced by these injection attacks. Consequently, TextSimu can function not only as a standalone text attack method for promoting target items but also can coordinate with injection attacks to wreak havoc on ID-free recommender systems. This finding raises significant concerns, emphasizing the need for sophisticated countermeasures in defending against TextSimu in such contexts.

Subsequently, we employed Gemma-2B as the LLM generator for the RewriteDetection. Table 4 shows that zero-shot Gemma-2B and ChatGLM2-6B were only slightly better than random guessing (i.e., 50%). This suggests that without access to attack data for fine-tuning, it is challenging to detect the generated text of TextSimu. Furthermore, our method outperforms the fine-tuned Gemma-2B and ChatGLM2-6B, which demonstrates a significant detection capability.
